{{Infobox person | name        = Dixie Brown | image       = Dixie Brown.jpg| alt         = | caption     = Dixie Brown, c. 1930| birth_name  = Anthony George Charles | birth_date  = 27 June 1900| birth_place = Castries, [[Saint Lucia]] | death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1957|04|20|1900|06|27}} | death_place = [[Bristol]] | nationality = British | other_names = | known_for   = | occupation  = Boxer }}

'''Anthony George Charles''' (born 27 June 1900 in [[Castries]], [[Saint Lucia]];<ref name=EMAS>{{cite web|url=http://www.emas4success.org/acrobat/TeachingMaterials/Biographies/BlackBristolians/Dixie_Brown.pdf |title=Dixie Brown Biography |first= |last= |work=Bristol Ethnic Minority Achievement Service |year=2009 |format=PDF |accessdate=9 July 2011 |page=17&ndash;18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006234739/http://www.emas4success.org/acrobat/TeachingMaterials/Biographies/BlackBristolians/Dixie_Brown.pdf |archivedate=6 October 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> died 20 April 1957) was a [[Boxing|boxer]], commonly known as '''Dixie Brown'''. He worked on the construction of the [[Panama Canal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thevoiceslu.com/features/2009/october/17_10_09/2nd_generation_offspring_of_famed_UK_boxer_visits_St_Lucia.htm|title=2nd generation offspring of famed UK boxer visits St Lucia|first=|last=Staff|work=The Voice, Saint Lucia|date=17 October 2009|accessdate=9 July 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006231530/http://www.thevoiceslu.com/features/2009/october/17_10_09/2nd_generation_offspring_of_famed_UK_boxer_visits_St_Lucia.htm|archivedate=6 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and emigrated to [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] in 1919.  In the [[West Country]] of England, he survived by working as a [[bare-knuckle boxing|bare-knuckle boxer]] in fairground booths. He moved with his wife, Lily Sellick, to [[Bristol]] in 1923, and registered as a professional boxer, fighting 85 bouts in the 1920s and 1930s, as [[welterweight]] and [[middleweight]]. He trained at the White Horse in Milk Street.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.lexisnexis.com/uk/nexis/results/docview/docview.do?docLinkInd=true&risb=21_T12319077115&format=GNBFI&sort=BOOLEAN&startDocNo=1&resultsUrlKey=29_T12319077118&cisb=22_T12319077117&treeMax=true&treeWidth=0&csi=166254&docNo=10 |title= We could make a book about the Pomphreys and boxing |first=R. |last=Wilson |work=Bristol Times |publisher=Bristol Evening Post, archived at LexisNexis |page=6&ndash;7 |date=29 June 1999 |subscription=yes |accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref> He could not contest any British championships owing to the colour bar then in operation.<ref name=clifdioc>{{cite web |url=http://www.cliftondiocese.com/assets/files/pdf/2007/december/Dixie%20Brown.pdf |title=Dixie Brown |format=PDF |first= |last= |work=cliftondiocese.com |year=2007 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323210901/http://www.cliftondiocese.com/assets/files/pdf/2007/december/Dixie%20Brown.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He had two wins, both over one-time champion Billy Green, five losses and two draws in his professional career.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=214449&cat=boxer |title=Dixie Brown - Boxer |first= |last= |work=boxrec.com |year=2011 |accessdate= 9 July 2011}}</ref>

Brown started family life in the "tough neighbourhood" of Philadelphia Street, [[St Jude's, Bristol|St Jude's]]. He was blinded in a fight in the 1930s and then moved with his family to [[Knowle West, Bristol]] after the [[Bristol Blitz|Blitz]].<ref name=engpast>{{cite web |url=http://explore.englandspastforeveryone.org.uk/items/dixie-brown |title=Dixie Brown |first= |last= |work=explore.englandspastforeveryone.org.uk |year=2011 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325101555/http://explore.englandspastforeveryone.org.uk/items/dixie-brown |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A collection was made to send him to the [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] shrine of [[Lourdes]] in France, in search of a cure.<ref name=clifdioc /> He was visited by many [[African American]] soldiers during the Second World War, as they respected him as "a well known and a much admired character".<ref name=EMAS /> Brown had nine children and thirty grandchildren. One of his grandsons used to take him to his local public house, the Venture Inn, where he had his own special chair.<ref name= engpast /> He was popular and well respected throughout Bristol. Brown died in 1957 and is buried in Holy Souls Catholic Cemetery next door to Arnos Vale Cemetery in Bristol.<ref name=EMAS /> Bristol historian Madge Dresser described him as "a family man who founded a virtual dynasty of Bristolians of mixed heritage, all of whom remember him with fondness."<ref name=clifdioc />

