'''Norman Howard Cliff''' (1925–2007) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Protestant]] author who wrote about Christianity and the history of [[Protestant missions in China]].
==Biography== Cliff was born in 1925 in [[Yantai]] (formerly, Chefoo) to Howard and Mary Cliff, both pharmacists who were working as missionaries with the [[China Inland Mission]] (CIM). As part of the [[Chefoo School]], a boarding school of the CIM, Cliff was interned by the Japanese at the [[Weixian Internment Camp]] from 1943 until 1945, when the camp was freed by American [[paratroopers]].<ref name="weihsien">{{Cite web|url=http://weihsien-paintings.org/NormanCliff/indexFrame.htm|title=The Life and Testimony of Norman Howard Cliff, 1925-2007|last=Horne|first=Estelle Cliffe|date=|website=Weihsien|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=7 February 2018}}</ref>
Cliff later went on to pursue a B.A. from the [[University of South Africa]] and a [[B.Com.]] from [[Rhodes University]]. He worked as a minister and an accountant for the [[United Reformed Church]] in South Africa, before returning to Britain due to poor health.<ref name="weihsien"/> Back in the UK, Cliff earned an [[MPhil]] at the [[Open University]] in 1983, writing a thesis on the theology of [[Watchman Nee]],<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Cliff|first=Norman Howard|title=The Life and Theology of Watchman Nee, Including a Study of the Little Flock Movement Which he Founded|date=1983|degree=MPhil|publisher=Open University|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/230634259/|doi=}}</ref> and a [[PhD]] at [[Buckingham University]] in 1995, writing a thesis on the history of Protestant missions in [[Shandong]] Province.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Cliff|first=Norman Howard|title=A history of the Protestant movement in Shandong Province, China, 1859-1951|date=1995|degree=PhD|publisher=University of Buckingham|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/304301557|doi=}}</ref>
==Works authored== * ''Prisoners of the Samurai: Japanese Civilian Camps, 1941-1945'' * ''Fierce the Conflict'' (2001) * ''White Cliffs of Hangzhou'' * ''Life and Theology of Watchman Nee : Including a Study of the Little Flock'' * ''A Heart for China: The Gripping Story of Benjamin Broomhall'' * ''A Flame of Sacred Love'' * ''Courtyard of the Happy Way''
